The goals of the project (1) to design and manufacture the VLF receiver stations for autonomous collecting of three components of magnetic field perturbations (based on the dB/dt magnetic loop antennas); and (2) to collect the data at Wallops during the flight of the VIPER rocket were achieved in full. 


The three-component VLF receiver stations were manufactured and calibrated. The autonomous time of data collecting is ~24-48 hours (depends on the batteries used). The data was collected during the VIPER flight in the vicinity of the rocket launch locations. Additionally, the data was collected in Berkeley, CA to supplement the measurements in Wallops. The coordinated processing of the data from VIPER and ground-based VLF receivers indicated the time moments of crossing ionosphere boundaries and the VLF wave power accumulation regions as well as the VLW wave power leakage through the ionosphere.

UC Berkeley developed and produced 8 preamplifiers for three-component measurements; 
The detectors were assembled, so two 3-component VLF/HF systems are available now;
The calibration of the detectors was carried out;
Fully autonomous operation of the assembled 3-component VLF/HF system was with the GPS log to control the 3D antennas orientation and time synchronization is tested for 24 hours sessions;
The measurements sessions were carried out in Berkeley, CA (April-May 2021, January 2022, 4 months in 2023), in Honolulu, HW (August 2021), in College Park, MD (February 2024), Denver (February 2024);
The field session to record the 3-components wave magnetic signal simultaneously with the VIPER rocket launch on May 26, 2021. The 1 day before and 1 day after measurements were recorded (May 25-27, 2022). 
The effects from the external factors (solar flares with the X-ray manifestations) to the ionosphere D-region were recorded and investigated
Teo postdoctoral researchers Scott Karbashwski and Kyung-Eun Choi worked on the project
The collaboration for multi-point VLF measuremetns with University of Colorado Denver and University of Colorado Boulder was established
The hardware design is used for the just started NSF project dedicated to multi-point observations of the ionosphere effects from the solar eclipse on April 8, 2024



